What it is
autobuild is a Makefile-driven toolkit for creating Ubuntu KVM guests on a libvirt host. It downloads official Ubuntu cloud images, builds per-VM qcow2 disks (root + optional swap/data/db/web), stitches together cloud-init (user-data, meta-data, network-config), and runs virt-install --import --cloud-init so the VM boots already configured. It is wired to your environment: tsand.org DNS, a local HTTP proxy in templates, SSH keys, and Ansible (inventory lines and a remote ansible host).

There is almost no application code beyond Make, shell one-liners, and template/sed assembly.

How a VM is built (main pipeline)
distro — Maps a short name (DISTRO, e.g. noble, resolute) to a cloud image URL and filename. Makefile reads this with egrep/cut.

sources → base → image — Downloads the image into $(SRCDIR), copies it to a base qcow2 under $(BASEDIR), then for each node creates a backing root disk under $(IMGDIR)/$(SNAME) (optionally resized with qemu-img resize).

role — The heart of customization. Starting from user-data-dir/$(DISTRO)/user-data.tmpl, it sed-inlines fragments from:

packages-dir/$(DISTRO)/packages-$(ROLE)
bootcmd-dir/..., mounts-dir/..., runcmd-dir/..., apt-dir/...
Placeholders in the template are #PACKAGES, #BOOTCMD, #MOUNTS, #RUNCMD, #APT.
disks — Optionally creates swap, data (under DATADIR), db / dblog, docroot qcow2s when the corresponding *SIZE variables are non-zero.

network-config — Either static (requires NAME to resolve via getent hosts for IPADDRESS) or DHCP, from network-config/$(DISTRO)/ templates.

meta-data — Writes instance id, hostname from NAME, injects ROLE / ENV, and your ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub.

node — Runs virt-install with the disks and cloud-init files, appends the host to /etc/ansible/hosts, syncs inventory to a remote Ansible machine, runs sshreset, starts the VM, and creates a fresh snapshot.

Other targets include Delete (destroy VM, pools, image dirs, prune Ansible), backup / live-backup, snapshot, and a librebooking playbook shortcut.

